This guidebook is the second edition of Ottavio Panciroli's I Tesori Nascosti nell’Alma Città di Roma originally published in the Holy Year of 1600, a fact that would explain the attention paid by this text to devotional practices, especially those that have to do with the Jubilee. The guida romana is here replaced by itineraries organized by the modern rioni (region or neighborhood). Despite the absence of illustrations, this guidebook gives a thorough art historical description of the Roman monuments from antiquity to the modern era. In the section dedicated to the Church of Santi Luca e Martina, the author mentions the church as being given to "i Pittori" (the painters) in 1588 by Sistus IV, following the Pope's decision to destroy the original Church of San Luca near Santa Maria Maggiore where the Compagnia dei Pittori was housed since 1478.

The Oratory of Sant’Orsola della Pietà was erected on the original site of the ancient church of Santi Orso e Tommaso, also called by its vernacular name of Sant’Orsola. The church was ceded to the Compagnia della Pietà della Nazione Fiorentina by Pope Clement VII in the middle of the 1520s, hence the appellation of Sant’Orsola della Pietà. It was also known as the Consolato (Consulate) because of its proximity to that site. The Oratory was demolished at the end of the 19th century for the creation of Corso Vittorio Emanuele II. This entry mentions the Oratory as being the repository until about the 1720s for Michelangelo’s preparatory drawings for the original project of the Church of San Giovanni dei Fiorentini.
